Interface BinaryTree<K,V>

  • Type Parameters:
    K - Generic type for keys
    V - Generic type for keys
    All Superinterfaces:
    DataStructure<K>, java.lang.Iterable<Pair<K,V>>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AVLTree, BinarySearchTree

    public interface BinaryTree<K,V>
extends DataStructure<K>, java.lang.Iterable<Pair<K,V>>
    All trees will implement this interface.

      • containsValue

        boolean containsValue(V value)
        Determines whether or not the tree contains a given value. Note, there may be multiple instances of the specified value, as the only thing that is unique in the tree is the key. This search will stop after the first instance of the value is found via pre-order traversal.
        Parameters:
        value - Value to look for.
        Returns:
        True if and only if the value is in the tree.

      • isBalanced

        boolean isBalanced()
        Determines whether or not the tree is balanced. A balanced tree is defined as a tree where for all subtrees of a given node, the maximum depth of the left subtree differs from the maximum depth of right subtree by at most one. An example follows: TODO - Insert image of example
        Returns:
        True if and only if the tree is balanced.

      • isComplete

        boolean isComplete()
        Determines whether or not the tree is complete. A complete tree is defined as a tree where all levels are filled, except possibly the bottom (deepest) level. In the event that the last level is not filled, all keys in tree are as left as possible. An example follows: TODO - Insert image of example
        Returns:
        True if and only if the above conditions are met.

      • isFull

        boolean isFull()
        Determines whether or not the tree is full. A full tree is defined as a tree where all nodes other than leaf nodes have two children. An example follows: TODO - Insert image of example
        Returns:
        True if the above condition is met.

      • isPerfect

        boolean isPerfect()
        Returns true if an only if the tree is perfect. A perfect tree is defined as a tree whether all nodes that are not leaf nodes have two children, and all leaf nodes are at the same level. An example follows: TODO - Insert image of example
        Returns:
        True if and only if the above conditions are met.

      • remove

        boolean remove(K key)
        Retrieves and removes a specified key from the tree. Algorithm inspired by http://www.algolist.net/Data_structures/Binary_search_tree/Removal
        Parameters:
        key - The specified key to remove from the tree.
        Returns:
        True if the node associate with the key was removed successfully.

      • removeValue

        default boolean removeValue(V value)
        Removes a value from the tree. Note, avoid removing by value if possible, as we must first find the node, then remove it. Finding the node by value requires a full traversal of the tree, whereas removing by key performs a binary search on the keys. The remove operation is still O(n) in the worst case though because a simple binary search tree may be linear.
        Parameters:
        value - Specified value to remove.
        Returns:
        True if the specified value was present and removed from the tree.
